 of the personal name   Oswald  ."]}]},{"name":"Knt.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Czeslawa, Zbigniew, Zygmunt, Bogdan, Boguslaw, Danuta, Dariusz, Dymitr, Elzbieta, Halina, Janina, Janusz.  Jewish Shlomo, Avraham.","Polish, Czech, Belorussian, and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): from Polish, Czech, and Belorussian <i>kot</i> ‘tom cat’, a nickname denoting either a cautious or a skillful person, or a seducer. As a Jewish name it is generally artificial. The homonymous Sorbian cognate <b>Kót</b> (from Lower Sorbian <i>kót</i> ‘tom cat’) is found in Germanized forms, only (see   Koth  ,   Kothe  ,   Kott  , and   Kotte  ). Compare also   Cott   4.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname 葛, see   Ge   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Kotas","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jozef, Justyna, Piotr, Wojciech.","Polish: derivative of   Kot   ‘cat’.","Czech: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Chotěbor</i>, meaning ‘warlike’."]},{"name":"Kotowicz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Czeslaw, Kazimierz, Krzysztof, Szczepan, Wladyslaw, Zdzislaw.","Polish and Jewish (from Poland): patronymic from   Kot  ."]},{"name":"Koth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Gerhard, Lorenz, Oskar.","German (also <b>Köth</b>): from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>kote</i> ‘cottage, hovel’, a status name for a day laborer who lived in a cottage and owned no farmland. Compare   Kotz  .","German: from a short form of any of various personal names formed with Old High German <i>got</i> ‘god’, for example <i>Gottfried</i>."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Baldwyn","type":"FIRST",